AIA, China Cosco, Cnooc, StanChart: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-04-18T00:51:07Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-17/china-cosco-cnooc-stanchart-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in  Hong Kong  trading. Stock symbols
are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last close.  The  Hang Seng Index (HSI)  was little changed at 24,008.07. The
Hang Seng  China  Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H
shares of Chinese companies, rose 0.4 percent to 13,533.58.  China banks and developers: China increased banks’ reserve
requirements to lock up cash and cool inflation, and central
bank Governor Zhou Xiaochuan said monetary tightening will
continue for “some time.”  Industrial & Commercial Bank of China (601398)  Ltd. (1398 HK), the
world’s No. 1 lender by market value, rose 0.5 percent to
HK$6.54.  China Construction Bank Corp. (939)  (939 HK), the second-
biggest, advanced 0.5 percent to HK$7.40.  China Resources Land Ltd. (1109)  (1109 HK), a state-controlled
developer, declined 2 percent to HK$14.60.  Shimao Property
Holdings Ltd. (813)  (813 HK), which gets all its revenue from China,
dropped 0.7 percent to HK$11.58.  AIA Group Ltd. (1299)  (1299 HK): The third-largest Asia-based
insurer by market value said its value of new business rose 21
percent to $182 million from a year earlier in the first quarter
as it sold more-profitable policies. The stock gained 1.2
percent to HK$25.05.  China Cosco (Holdings) Co. (1919 HK):  Oil prices  may drop
to about $82 per barrel, Chairman Wei Jiafu said. Prices may
decline in the second half of this year or next year, he said.
Cosco Group may expand its fleet of very large crude carriers as
China boosts oil imports, Wei said. The stock fell 0.1 percent
to HK$8.03.  Cnooc Ltd. (883)  (883 HK): China’s biggest offshore oil producer
said it has appointed Wang Yilin as chairman of the board and
non-executive director. The stock was unchanged at HK$19.58.  Huaneng Power International Inc. (902)  (902 HK): The company said
its electricity output in the first quarter of the year rose 29
percent to 75.4 billion kilowatt-hours from a year earlier. The
stock advanced 1.1 percent to HK$4.58.  Standard Chartered Plc (STAN)  (2888 HK): The lender will raise
 mortgage rates  linked to Hong Kong’s interbank offered rate, or
Hibor,  Radio Television Hong Kong  reported, without citing where
it obtained the information. The stock slid 0.2 percent to
HK$207.80.  Mingfa Group (International) Co. (846 HK): The developer
said its unit will acquire an 80 percent stake in Dowence
Development Ltd. for HK$800 million, according to a stock
exchange filing. The agreement will be settled in cash and
through share transfer agreements, the statement said. The stock
was unchanged at HK$2.59.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in  Tokyo  at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
